    Let <fr:tex>u\colon  Y_\bullet \to  X_\bullet </fr:tex> be a morphism of topological simplicial spaces, with cone <fr:tex>C(u)</fr:tex>.
    Let <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> be an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex>X_\bullet </fr:tex> and <fr:tex>G</fr:tex> an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex>Y_\bullet </fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex>f\colon  G\to  F</fr:tex> be a <fr:tex>u</fr:tex>-morphism.
    The cone <fr:tex>C(f)</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> is an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex>C(u)</fr:tex>, and we set

    <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2317</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>6.3.2.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block">         \operatorname {H}^n(C(u),C(f))         = \operatorname {H}^n(X_\bullet \operatorname {mod} Y_\bullet , F\operatorname {mod} G).       \tag{6.3.2.1}       </fr:tex></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>

    These are the <fr:em>relative cohomology groups</fr:em>.
    We can easily show that they fit into a long exact sequence

    <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
